        <name>7.2.7.2 Exercise 2</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let \(A = {@A@}\) and \(B = {@B@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Is it true that \(AB=BA\)? [[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt; GIven that \(AB = \begin{bmatrix}\cos{z} &amp;amp; \sin{z} \\ -\sin{z} &amp;amp; \cos{z}\end{bmatrix}\), what is \(z\) in terms of \(x\) and \(y\)? [[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the matrices
    \(A = {@A@}\)
    and
    \(B = {@B@}\).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;First, we are asked whether \(AB = BA\), that is, whether \(A\) and \(B\) commute. In order to answer this question, we must find what \(AB\) and \(BA\) are.&lt;/p&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        AB &amp;amp;= {@ABsteps@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@AB@}
        \end{aligned}\]
        \[\begin{aligned}
        BA &amp;amp;= {@BAsteps@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@BA@}
        \end{aligned}\]
        &lt;p&gt;Checking each entry at a time, we see that \(AB\) is in fact equal to \(BA\).&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;We already computed the value of \(AB\) in part (a). However, it was not fully simplified.&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Recall the trigonometric identities for the sum of angles:&lt;/p&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        \sin(x + y) &amp;amp;= \sin x \cos y + \sin y \cos x \\
        \cos(x + y) &amp;amp;= \cos x \cos y - \sin x \sin y
        \end{aligned}\]
        &lt;p&gt;Using these, we can rewrite our expression for \(AB\) as&lt;/p&gt;
        \[{@ABfinal@}\]
        &lt;p&gt;Therefore, the value of \(z\) we are asked for is \(x + y\).&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
